1. Avg_Credit_Limit - The average is 34574 and standard deviation is 37625. The minimum is 3000 which is within (mean-3 std dev). Thus there are no ouliers on left side of the curve. 2. Total_Credit_cards - The mean is 4.7 and the standard deviation is 2.17. The minimum is 1 which is within (mean-3 std dev). The maximum is 10 which too is within (mean_3 std dev) which is 11.21. So the variable Total_Credit_Cards has no outlier.¶

4. Total_visits_online - The minimum being 0.0 is more than mean-3Std Dev thus no oulier of left side of curve. The max is 15 which compared to mean+3 Std Dev i.e. 11.41 is more. Thus on right side of the distribution of Total_visits_online there are outlier. Thus there are no outliers.¶

5. Total_calls_made - The mean is 3.58 and Standard deviation is 2.86. The minimum being 0 is within mean-3std Dev. And, the maximum being 10 is also within (mean+3 std dev). Therefore the variable Total_calls_made has no outliers.¶

Fixing Outliers¶

As we have seen above outlier are present in the given dataset. There are multiple ways to deal with outliers but we mostly prefer either to drop the outliers or repalce it.¶

Since there is not too much data given to begin with so dropping rows with outliers will only make the data set that much poorer. Therefore we will replace the outliers. Since the outliers are on the right side so we will replace these with mean+ 3 * Std. This way we will not lose some important information and also not reduce the total of thses outliers by instead repalcing with the median values.¶

I have also shown the number of outliers presence in each column in below code.¶

In [18]:
for col_name in customer_df.columns[:-2]:
    q1 = customer_df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = customer_df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
#    low = q1-1.75*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr
    
    customer_df.loc[(customer_df[col_name] > high), col_name] = high
    
   # dfconcrete_new.loc[(dfconcrete_new[col_name] < low) | (dfconcrete_new[col_name] > high), col_name] = dfconcrete_new[col_name].median()

Group into similar Clusters¶

Here we are trying to find the optimal number of clusters for K-Means methos of clustering¶

In [29]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(customerScaled)
    prediction=model.predict(customerScaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(customerScaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / customerScaled.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[29]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

As observed from the curve above we can see the elbow is at K=3. This indicates that the with 3 clusers we can acheive optimal seggregation / segmentation of the given customer data. We will now proceed with 3 clusters to execute K-Means clustering¶

Analysis the box Plots¶

From the mean of the three clusters we can clearly make the following observations:¶

1. Group 0 are the customers who have highest average credit limit. This group also has the highest number of Credit card with the average of the group being around 8 cards. And this goup has the highest online visits compared to other two groups. This group therefore has less number of visits to the bank and also least number of calls made to the bank. Thus, this group of high credit limits conducts its banking business more through internet insteaf of physical visits or telephonic calls.¶

2. Group 1 is the cluster which comprises of customers with least average credit limit of aroundn 12K USD. This group also has the least number of average credit cards per customer of just over 2 cards. The number of average visits on line are also higherThis group makes the highest number of calls to the bank but their visits to the bank are higher than Group 0's but less than those of average total visits to the bank by Group 2.¶

3. Group 2 is the cluster with medium level of average credit limit and medium number of credit cards owned by each customer of this group. This group also has medium level of total_calls_made i,e, it is more than those made by Group0 but less than the calls made by cystomer in group 1.¶

Analysis the box Plots¶

From the mean of the three clusters we can make the following observations, which are similar to that of analysis of K-Means clustering box-plots except that the Group number are swapped wrt those of K-Means clustering:¶

1. Group 0 is the cluster with medium level of average credit limit and medium number of credit cards owned by each customer of this group. This group alos has medium level of total_calls_made i,e, it is more than those made by Group1 but less than the calls made by cystomer in group 2.¶

2. Group 1 are the customers who have highest average credit limit. This group also has the highest number of Credit cards. And this goup has the highest online visits compared to other two groups. This groupd therefore has less number of visits to the bank and also least number of calls made to the bank. Thus, this group of high credit limits conducts its banking business more through internet insteaf of physical visits or telephonic calls.¶

3. Group 2 is the cluster which comprises of customers with least average credit limit. This group also has the least number of average credit cards per customer of just over 2 cards. The number of average visits on line are also higherThis group makes the highest number of calls to the bank but their visits to the bank are higher than Group 1's but less than those of average total visits to the bank by Group 0.¶

7 Analysis the clusters formed, tell us how is one cluster different from another and answer all the key questions¶

7a. How is one cluster different from another:¶

As per the detailed analysis of the segmentation of the clusters the three clusters Group0, Group1 and Group2 have been based on average values of the 5 attributes viz. average_credit_limit, total_credit_cards, total_visits_online, total_calls_made and total_visits_bank.¶

Broad characteristics of each group:¶

Group1: This cluster has customers who have and can afford highest credit_limit and highest average total_credit_cards. This group of customers don't have time to make visits to bank due to which they have the lowest total_visits_bank. This group of customers also has lowest total_calls_made and they rely on contacting the bank through internet i.e. this group relies heavily on use of technology when conducting business with the bank. Thus Group1 has the highest average total_visits_online.¶

Group2: This cluster of customers are on the other side of spectrum compared to Group1 customers. Customers assigned to Group2 have the lowest average number of average_credit_limit and therefore also have least number of total_credit_cards. This group conducts its business with the bank primarily by contacting via phone due to which this group has the highest number of total_calls_made. This group also relies, though moderately compared to contact via telephone, on physical visits to bank and accessing bank account and doing transactions via internet.¶

Group0: This is the intermediate group of customers i.e. this group has lower average_credit_limit and total_credit_cards compared to customers of Group1 but higher than those of customers assigned to Group2. This group makes least use of the technology i.e. has the lowest average total_visits_online and relies modelrately on contacting bank via telephone since they have 2nd highest average of total_calls_made. This group, on an average, places more importance on interacting with the bank in-person since their total_bank_vists are by far the highest compared to other two groups of customers.¶

Answer all key questions:¶

1. How many different segments of customers are there?¶

2. How are these segments different from each other?¶

3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?¶

1. Answer to question "How many different segments of customers are there?"¶

There are primarily three segments of customers the bank's customer base can be divided into. These are represeented by Group0, Group1 and Group2 as per our analysis above.¶

2. Answer to question "How are these segments different from each other?"¶

These three clusters or groups of customers differ based on the two primary differentiators: 1. Value of business and 2. Mode of conducting business with the bank or contacting the bank.¶

a. Based on value of business: The customers can be divided into three groups based on the level of average_credit_limit and high total_credit_cards as :i) 'High' i.e. Group1, ii) 'Intermediate' i.e. Group0 and finally iii)' Low' - Group2 belongs to this level.¶

b.Mode of conducting business with the bank or contacting the bank: The customers have been divided into three clusters based on their preference of the mode they use for contacting the bank or conducting business with the bank. This differentiator can be seggregated into the following classes based on 'Reliance on technology': within this we have three sub-classes: i) High Technology: Group1 belongs to this group as its average total_visits_online is the highest, ii) Intermediate Technology: Group2 belongs to this sub-class as it makes use of online lesser than Group1 but more than Group0 and finally iii) Low technology: This is the group that makes least usage of technology when contacting the bank as eviident in their least total_visits_online and instead rely most on making inperson visits to the bank as shown by highest total_bank_visits.¶

3. Answer to the question "What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?"¶

The bank should use the two differentiators as mentioned above in response to Question#2, Thus, the bank should make use of the "Value of Business" they have with the customer and the "Level of Technology" used by customer to target their specific services and mode of reaching out to their target customer segment.¶

The bank should focus marketing their high value services to Group1 of customers. The bank should use technology and create marketing content on web and send it to the Group1 to marker the high end services.¶

The bank can target Group0 and Group2 for basic services and leverage mobile / telephony to market these services. This can be used especially for Group2 cluster of customers. The banks can also use their customer care representatives in their bank locations to 'greet and meet' expecially Group0 customers.¶
